Backport: raid5_set_limits guards max_hw_wzeroes_unmap_sectors pre-6.18

The struct queue_limits.max_hw_wzeroes_unmap_sectors field was added
in upstream around kernel 6.18 (see commit 0c1af234 "md: init
queue_limits->max_hw_wzeroes_unmap_sectors parameter"). Older kernels'
struct queue_limits has no such field.

The single assignment in raid5_set_limits initializes it to 0, which
matches the implicit default when the field doesn't exist. Guard the
assignment with a version check.

--- a/raid5.c
+++ b/raid5.c
@@ -7790,7 +7790,9 @@ static int raid5_set_limits(struct mddev *mddev)
 	lim.discard_granularity = stripe;
 	lim.max_hw_discard_sectors = 0;
 	lim.max_write_zeroes_sectors = 0;
+#if LINUX_VERSION_CODE >= KERNEL_VERSION(6, 18, 0)
 	lim.max_hw_wzeroes_unmap_sectors = 0;
+#endif
 	mddev_stack_rdev_limits(mddev, &lim, 0);
 	return queue_limits_set(mddev->gendisk->queue, &lim);
 }
